@Mikey Parmar

Real-world smarts need to be accompanied by crossword experience to do well on Saturdays here. I've been doing this for almost two years and I got a huge majority of today's clues - and I'm not even a native speaker of English, nor am I familiar with American culture.

The first NYT puzzles I did were humbling. Persevere and you and your girlfriend will become experts at this.

@Mikey Parmar 

I worked most of my life in industrial bakeries and warehouses, either doing manual labor or operating various machines, but I managed to do this puzzle. 

Crossword solving isn't just just a measure of trivial knowledge or intelligence, although those definitely help. It's a skill that improves with experience.

@Mikey Parmar
I'm not taking the MCAT--in fact, I only have a high school diploma, from a critically underfunded high school in a rural South Dakota town.

And I still managed to do this puzzle. I actually thought it was easier than the Thursday and Friday puzzles this week.

@Margaret from Brooklyn

Aside from what Beth said about humility or lack thereof, I didn't find one thing in the original post that indicated that "him and his girlfriend" were novices to crosswords.

And I suspect this was a drive-by; he wasn't hanging around for an answer.

@Francis

I on the other hand find the American system strangely souless and impersonal. It's obviously very practical and literally makes sense, unlike what I am used to, but I like how our street names celebrate people, history, culture, nature, geography.

For example, I lived the first 15 years of my life on ulica Zamiany - Swap Street. Swap Street? Whaaat? Well, that part of town was built in the 1970s to replace fields and villages that had been there for centuries. Once, two noblemen exchanged villages in the area, and one of the settlements was renamed Zamiana (Swap) to commemorate the event. Centuries later, the village disappeared forever, but its name had been preserved in the street name. Many street names in the Ursyn√≥w district have similar etymologies.

@W johnson

In the US, it's common for streets to be named after what used to be there.  Sometimes, this is intentional.  A shopping center was built near here in Montvale, NJ, and the new street it is on was named Farm View.  Of course, the farm was where the shopping center is now.

Sometimes, it's not as intentional, even though the namers of streets should probably realize that the street might outlast the thing it was named for.  Wall Street is perhaps the best-known example of this.  In Paramus, NJ, the two streets leading to the Paramus Park mall are called A&S Drive and Sears Drive, after two department stores that were in the shopping center originally, but are long gone now.

@Bruce

Sure, I'm not disputing any of that.

However, nowhere in Europe have I seen numbered and lettered streets and avenues like in some American cities. I'm not denying American diversity, but some solutions are common enough in the US and virtually known elsewhere for the former to be identified as American, specifically.

@Nancy J.

